Frontend & Design Spec — v1
Project: PRINTR Powerball — public-facing site for a 15-minute on-chain raffle.
Audience: Design / frontend agent. The backend spec defines the data; this doc defines how it's shown.
v1 scope: the site is read-only — no wallet connection, no user accounts, no inputs. The frontend polls a few REST endpoints and renders. Equal odds for every eligible wallet (no weighting in v1).

1. Brand & Vibe
This is a lottery, but degenerate-crypto-flavored and radically transparent. Two energies in tension that we want both of:

Hype — countdown timers, big numbers, winners flashing across the screen, that "next round in 4:23" anticipation.
Trust — every claim backed by a tx hash you can click. No marketing fluff. The site looks like it was built by people who understand the chain.

Reference points (vibe, not copy):

Pump.fun / PRINTR's own aesthetic — crypto-native, no corporate polish
Polymarket — data-dense but readable, every number sourced
Stake.com / Rollbit — the lottery hype motion language
Etherscan — the trust language: monospace addresses, raw data, link-everything

Avoid: Web3 startup template look (gradient-on-purple-on-glassmorphism), generic SaaS pastels, anything that feels like a Stripe landing page.

2. Visual Language
Theme
Dark first, always. Light mode is optional polish, not a priority.
Color palette
Background base    #0A0B0F   (almost black, slight blue)
Surface 1          #12141A   (cards)
Surface 2          #1A1D26   (raised cards, modals)
Border subtle      #232733
Border emphasis    #2F3441

Text primary       #F5F6FA
Text secondary     #9BA1B0
Text muted         #5A6072

Accent — win/gold     #FFC940   (winners, prize pool, the main accent)
Accent — live/green   #00E59D   (live indicators, "eligible", positive deltas)
Accent — alert/red    #FF4D5E   (drops, warnings, sells)
Accent — cool/violet  #8B5CF6   (secondary, links, info)
Gold is the hero color — use sparingly so it stays special. Reserve it for the prize amount, the winner reveal, and the countdown when it goes under 60s.
Typography

Display / headings: sharp geometric sans — Space Grotesk, Geist, or Satoshi. Heavy weights (600–800) for big numbers.
Body: Inter or Geist Sans, 14–16px.
Mono (addresses, tx hashes, numbers in tables): JetBrains Mono, Geist Mono, or IBM Plex Mono. Tabular figures on for any countdown or amount.

Two font families maximum. Hierarchy via weight + size, not new fonts.
Iconography
Lucide or Phosphor. Line style, 1.5px stroke.
Motion principles

Numbers count up, never just appear (tween for prize pool, holder counts)
Live elements pulse subtly to signal real-time-ness — single green dot at 1s cadence
Round transitions feel like a slot machine settling — quick build, satisfying snap, no long Lottie animations
prefers-reduced-motion respected — kill pulses and counters, keep transitions


